      {
        "id": 3956952,
        "name": "Mark Golodetz",
        "username": "Mark_Golodetz",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/mark_golodetz/{size}/76850_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-12-23T03:03:17.057Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Very weird. I seemed to have deleted my own topic.</p>\n<p>I love older Beychevelle. It settles down nicely with age, a lighter more perfumed style of Bordeaux, with occasional notes that are slightly reminiscent of Burgundy. Two vintages the 1959 and 1928 are more than slightly, they are drop dead doppelg\u00e4ngers of a great Vosne; and as I have several bottles of the 1959, it is fun to serve blind in a flight of older Cote de Nuits.</p>\n<p>Getting back to the 1966, high to top shoulder, great color. But when I took off the capsule, there was a smell of ancient wine, and when I removed the cork, I got a blast of the same older notes.</p>\n<p>But that was it for the problems.<br>\nAfter decanting the wine began to blossom. Showed strawberry, menthol, and ginger. Very savory. Love the balance, plenty of acid, easy progression to an unexpectedly long finish. As the wine stayed in the glass, it began to take on woodsy and iron notes, while the fruit stayed, happily playing off the new flavors. Altogether a very, very good bottle 95</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 7,
        "updated_at": "2022-12-23T03:03:56.947Z",
