      {
        "id": 3957050,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-12-23T07:53:35.074Z",
        "cooked": "<p>When you look at the Masnaghetti map of the M\u00e9doc estates, one of the striking things is just how much top terroir Beychevelle has. Quite a lot of the vineyards one might easily assume belong to Ducru Beaucaillou actually belong to Beychevelle. Just in terms of terroir, I would venture that they have clear super-second potential. Today, the style is quite chunky and extracted, again somewhat in contrast to the historical reputation for supple, giving wines.</p>",
